A BILL FOR AN ACT
RELATING TO ISLAND BURIAL COUNCILS.
BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF HAWAII:
1 SECTION 1. The legislature finds that the protection of
2 iwi kupuna (ancestral remains) is a matter of utmost cultural
3 and historical importance. Island burial councils play a
4 critical role in safeguarding burial sites and advising the
5 department of land and natural resources in decisions affecting
6 Native Hawaiian ancestral remains. However, the effectiveness
7 of the councils has been limited by persistent vacancies,
8 uncompensated service, and insufficient staff support. These
9 challenges are particularly severe on less populated islands,
10 where councils often fail to meet quorum, preventing lineal and
11 cultural descendants from having a meaningful voice in decisions
12 about the treatment of iwi kupuna and exercising their right to
13 self-determination. Council members are further required to
14 attend lengthy meetings and engage in consultations for
15 inadvertent discoveries within their moku (region), adding to
16 these constraints.
